*Rating*: :( Bad

{panel:title=What do you like?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#c2ffa2|bgColor=#fff}
The doc I see explains how to solve my problem
{panel}

{panel:title=What needs to be improved?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#faacad|bgColor=#fff}
The doc is not up-to-date with bitbucket hosted solution : how do I actually setup server hooks ? "Hooks" do not appear anywhere in my settings, as the settings menu I have is not the same as the one in this page's screenshots
{panel}

*Reporter*: Robin
*E-mail*: [mailto:robin@supermood.fr]

h3. Problem Definition

Support zip should capture the hooks which are enabled for repositories. Having this information beforehand, will help in debugging, troubleshooting third-party hooks related issues etc. especially when the issue is narrowed down to a single repository.
h3. Suggested Solution

Have the hooks related information in application.xml in support zip along with other repository details.
h3. Workaround

This information can be retrieved from database with below query
{code:java}
SELECT * FROM public.sta_repo_hook;
{code}
{noformat}
id | repository_id | hook_key | is_enabled | lob_id
------------------------------------------------------------------
22 | 536 | at.apogeum.bitbucket.checkstyle:checkstyle-receive-repository-hook | f |
24 | 761 | com.atlassian.stash.plugin.stash-web-post-receive-hooks-plugin:postReceiveHook | t | 674
23 | 761 | de.aeffle.stash.plugin.stash-http-get-post-receive-hook:http-get-post-receive-hook | f | 673
{noformat}
For a specific repository, with the repository ID
{code:java}
SELECT * FROM public.sta_repo_hook where repository_id = repository ID; 
{code}

h3. Summary

After a hook has been created, {{RepositoryHookDao.findByKey(internalRepository, hookKey)}} returns {{null}}. However, {{RepositoryHookService.getById(hookId)}} returns the record.

h3. Environment
* Tested against 5.1.6 + H2
* Customer reports failures from 5.0 onwards (see Notes)

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a hook through {{RepositoryHookDao.create()}}
# Retrieve it through {{RepositoryHookDao.findByKey(internalRepository, hookKey)}}

h3. Expected Results
The created record is returned.

h3. Actual Results
{{null}} is returned.
 
h3. Notes
Originally asked in [this Community post|https://community.developer.atlassian.com/t/failure-to-enable-repository-hook-and-to-change-its-settings/8705].

We ran the plug-in of the customer and could reproduce the behaviour against 5.1.6 while debugging (breakpoint in {{RepositoryHookService.enable()}}):
* {{RepositoryHookService.getById(hookId)}} returns record
* {{RepositoryHookDao.findByKey(internalRepository, hookKey)}} returns {{null}}
* {{RepositoryHookDao.findAll(internalRepository, new PageRequestImpl(0,200))}} does not return the record

However, when writing a test to validate:

{code}        InternalRepository one = repositoryDao.loadById(1);
        String hookKey = "some.hook.key";
        String data = "{\"cloneType\":\"http\",\"ignoreCerts\":true,\"jenkinsBase\":\"http://localhost\"}";
        InternalRepositoryHook.Builder hookBuilder = new InternalRepositoryHook.Builder()
                .hookKey(hookKey)
                .repository(convertToInternalRepository(one))
                .enabled(true);
        hookBuilder.settings(data);

        dao.create(hookBuilder.build());
        InternalRepositoryHook hook = dao.findByKey(one, hookKey);
        assertNotNull(hook);{code}

We could *not* reproduce the issue (above test passes). Still, we are confident this is a bug in Bitbucket Server.

h3.Workaround
Not applicable.

h2. Problem
The documentation for installing and configuring a remote Elasticsearch instance contains a very misleading first step:

{quote}
# Download the Buckler plugin on the remote machine:
|*Elasticsearch 2.3.5*|[Buckler 0.2.12 for ES 2.3.5|https://maven.atlassian.com/content/groups/public/com/atlassian/elasticsearch/buckler-plugin/0.2.12/buckler-plugin-0.2.12-2.3.5.zip?_ga=2.236362177.1578624197.1501880211-43306010.1447648178]|
# Install the plugin onto your remote Elasticsearch instance using the plugin helper in the Elasticsearch /bin directory: {code}
cd /path/to/elasticsearch/bin
./plugin install -b <link from table above>
{code}
{quote}

The first step, "Download the Buckler plugin" is incorrect and unnecessary. Elasticsearch's plugin installer accepts a _url_, and will handle downloading the plugin on its own. Users should therefore _not_ download the plugin, despite what the first instruction says. 

h2. Solution
Change Step 1 to "Copy the Buckler plugin URL to your clipboard", or else remove Step 1 altogether.

h3. Summary

Bitbucket Server throws error when tries to fetch a raw json with Accept header (Content-type: application/json) specified

h3. Steps to Reproduce

 curl -H "Accept: application/json" -H "Content-type: application/json" -X GET https://<URL>/projects/<project>/repos/<repo>/raw/file.json

h3. Expected Results

It returns the raw contents of the file.

h3. Actual Results

For versions before 5.3.0, this returns 

{noformat}
{"message":"null for uri: https://<URL>/projects/<project>/repos/<repo>/raw/file.json","status-code":404} 
{noformat}

and for versions 5.3.0+, this returns 
{noformat}
{"message":"null for uri: https://<URL>/projects/<project>/repos/<repo>/raw/file.json","status-code":500}
{noformat}
h3. Workaround

Replace {{https://<URL>/projects/<project>/repos/<repo>/raw/file.json}} with 
 {noformat}https://<URL>/mvc/projects/<project>/repos/<repo>/raw/file.json{noformat}

